                    <h2>The Biology of Why</h2>
                    
                    <p>To understand why sleep is foundational, we need to look at what happens in your body across a 24-hour cycle. It's a symphony of biological processes, and sleep is the conductor.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>2:00 AM - Deep Sleep</strong>: Your body temperature hits its lowest point. Growth hormone surges, repairing muscles and consolidating memories. The glymphatic system is power-washing your brain, clearing out the day's metabolic waste.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>4:00 AM - REM Peak</strong>: Your final and longest REM period is processing emotions, solving problems, and preparing you for the day ahead. Miss this, and you wake emotionally fragile and cognitively impaired.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>6:00 AM - Cortisol Awakening</strong>: If you've slept well, cortisol rises sharply, naturally waking you with energy. If you haven't, this response is blunted, and you need an alarm to drag you from bed.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>10:00 AM - Peak Alertness</strong>: With good sleep, this is when complex problem-solving peaks. Without it, you're still trying to "wake up" with your third cup of coffee.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>2:00 PM - Natural Dip</strong>: Everyone experiences an afternoon lull, but well-rested people have a shallow dip. Sleep-deprived people crash hard, reaching for sugar or more caffeine.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>6:00 PM - Physical Peak</strong>: Athletic performance peaks here—if you're rested. If not, injury risk is elevated and performance is compromised.</p>
                    
                    <p><strong>9:00 PM - Melatonin Rise</strong>: In a healthy system, melatonin begins rising, preparing you for sleep. In a disrupted system, you get a "second wind" that keeps you up too late, perpetuating the cycle.</p>
                    
                    <p>Every single point in this cycle affects your ability to make good choices, stick to habits, and become who you want to be. And every single point is governed by the quality and quantity of your sleep.</p>

